vote_reason: One of the more serious issues we are facing in our world today is inadequate  and underfunded drug policy reform education for the youth of the world. We have been challenged by a 'drug free' media, by 'banned' substance rhetoric and general 'abstinence based' propaganda messages that take us away from the issues of a scientific health and evidenced based approach to drug eduction. We must encourage a regulatory and taxed based approach for cannabis and send a vital message to all governments to legalize and tax all drugs and make drug education worthy of our support. If we are to ban anything it would be to take the failed and misguided directions of the D.A.R.E. program and replace it with information that is based in: honesty, respect and assistance when needed as the directives. We are Educators for Sensible Drug Policy. Please, visit our website.  http://www.efsdp.org  Our official Facebook address: www.facebook.com/EFSDP We are  an official registered not-for-profit drug policy reform organization made up of school trustees/superintendents/teachers/parents who want to see the end of prohibition. Prisons are not the  drug classrooms for the future of our children.  The 'from school to prison pipeline' must be stopped and as  dedicated and passionate drug policy reformers and educators we have made excellent progress. More needs to be done.

suggested_priority: I want "A World without Borders". In my personal opinion, we can't actually have peace unless we give up on the idea of what's  yours and what's mine. We humans are the same. A single country or a religion or a colour should not make us superior or inferior. I don't think we cannot achieve peace if we stay patriotic to a single country because it creates division.

vote_reason: I prioritized fulfilling basic needs of the world population such as eating, drinking, being in good health, and living in a sound environment. Because once people feel secure they can think about tomorrows without having to fight for their daily needs through violence, and they have the mental space to build a better future for themselves and their relatives.

I'm frustrated by the repeated verbage from politicians, business people  and their associated lobby groups who believe that the only way that we are going to have a better world is if we grow more food to feed what is predicted to be a burgeoning  population. 

We simply have to stop using as much grain as we do to feed livestock, thereby dramatically taking the pressure off the demand for oil and its derivatives into agriculture, agrochemicals, water to grow crops to feed livestock,  the tinkering with genetics that the genetic manipulators are undertaking and more. Furthermore, if we do this, we will end up with a much more vegetarian diet, and therefore much less demand upon our health restoring services and hospitals. We will have healthier people. As a final bonus we will also have much fragile land that we can put back into grassland and/or forests, thereby preserving the only thing that the world absolutely cannot do without – soil.  I say all this as a farmer, one that is aware of what's happening to the resources of agriculture – the soil  and the natural environment – and can see the need to act in a way that may not be necessarily in my best interest personally, but is in the best interest of  the next generation

What's so difficult about doing that? Is it a lack of political will? Is it  a failing of a political system that demands short-term government's who can't take a long-term view? Is it the ever-increasing power of the multinational corporations? Is it the dominance of the lobbyists who work on their behalf within and on the fringes of government? Is there corruption that prevents this logical change?

To make these logical things happen will require politicians and others to act with commitment and a lack of fear for their own well-being and job security. Let's hope there are some of those with  such redeeming qualities who can  act in the right way and save the planet from self-destruction.
